name: Joshua Garcia - Kimble
title: CS at Harvey Mudd College | Presidential Scholar
summary:
Why Computer Science
For me, computer science is a tool that I wield in order to give people more free time and make others’ free time more fun. That free time can be created by producing a program that streamlines a certain process in a meeting or that free time can be made more enjoyable with a challenging game. Whatever the case, I want people to have more time in their day to do what they want.

My Approach to Learning
But computer science can be a hard tool to wield. It requires learning C++ to build data structures, learning object-oriented programming to create projects, learning algorithms to run programs with efficient Big O time, and much more. But for me, the challenge of learning these pieces is what makes it worthwhile. Being able to go down to the most basic layer of a program or concept and connect the constituent pieces to build it back up is the fun of it. Sure, sometimes I may have to scratch a whole idea, but the insight I get from learning why it did not work adds to the pieces I can connect in the future.

Favorite Project
My favorite project was creating an alignment system for my robotics team. Simply put, with a press of a button, the robot would align itself with the goal and score. With that capability, my team would not only be able to score goals faster, but more members would be able to operate the robot as the skill ceiling would have been drastically lower. Not only did this capability create more free time for them to score in the game, but it was also really cool to see the robot align itself to score.

Future Professional Interests
To expand my repertoire of tools, I am currently interested in learning more about augmented and virtual reality development, spatial computing, computer vision, and deep learning.

If any of this interests you, please do not be afraid to reach out to me 🙂

To manage the project I used Git for version control.

member_projects_collection.name: Automated Greenhouse
member_projects_collection.description: Designed, as part of a team, an automatic greenhouse utilizing sensors and microcontrollers. Uses two PIC18F4520 microcontrollers from Microchip. One microcontroller is the main controller while the other one handles display and user input. The system has 6 total collecting units: ambient light sensor, water level sensor, pH sensor, RPM sensor, temperature sensor and finally a humidity sensor. A pair of fluorescent lights and an incandescent light is used to allow for a full spectrum of light. The incandescent light also acts as a source of heat. A bilge blower is used for humidity and temperature control. The system uses both an ATX computer power supply and the mains voltage for power. A GLCD with touch screen capabilities is used for user input and display.

member_experience_collection.title: Senior Manager, Engineering
member_experience_collection.description:
Mission: lead all engineering disciplines to develop innovative and reliable products, and become the partner of choice for our Customers and Suppliers
• Addressed the people by talent acquisition and skill development; diversified the team competences and promoted dissemination of the expertise; Initiated a succession plan and set up the ground for future team leaders. With a team of +40 Engineers, the key enabler was to make sure people were comfortable working with each other. The most skillful individuals become useless to the organization if they were not approachable.
• Addressed the Products: enabled the team members to build intimate knowledge of the products and customer requirements; established and defended program budgets; developed and executed product roadmaps; completed backlog of product qualifications and launched new product designs and innovations.
• Addressed the processes: set up and enforced TRL based gated review process, defined and tracked engineering KPIs, established in-house software certification process, achieved Airbus technical delegation, ensured adherence to AS9100 procedures and compliance to industry standards by design assurance coordination and internal engineering audits.

This experience was of the most amazing professional journey; I was grateful to have mentors who would help harness my passion and give shape to my "crazy" ideas. I was thankful to have a team which allowed me to innovate, try and fail, but never stopped supporting my initiatives. They taught me that loyalty is a consequence of leadership. By far, I believe our greatest achievement was to see so many engineers grow their talent in this environment and now contribute to the global Zodiac Aerospace engineering community.

Definitely a lot of lessons learned as well that I cannot wait to apply onto my next assignment
.
Key words: Team development, Program Management, Leadership, Certification,
Configuration Management, Reliability, Process Improvement,

member_experience_collection.title: Senior Manager, Engineering
member_experience_collection.description:
Mission: lead all engineering disciplines to develop innovative and reliable products, and become the partner of choice for our Customers and Suppliers
•  Addressed the people by talent acquisition and skill development; diversified the team competences and promoted dissemination of the expertise; Initiated a succession plan and set up the ground for future team leaders. With a team of +40 Engineers, the key enabler was to make sure people were comfortable working with each other. The most skillful individuals become useless to the organization if they were not approachable.
• Addressed the Products: enabled the team members to build intimate knowledge of the products and customer requirements; established and defended program budgets; developed and executed product roadmaps; completed backlog of product qualifications and launched new product designs and innovations.
• Addressed the processes: set up and enforced TRL based gated review process, defined and tracked engineering KPIs, established in-house software certification process, achieved Airbus technical delegation, ensured adherence to AS9100 procedures and compliance to industry standards by design assurance coordination and internal engineering audits.

This experience was of the most amazing professional journey;  I was grateful to have mentors who would help harness my passion and give shape to my "crazy" ideas. I was thankful to have a team which allowed me to innovate, try and fail, but never stopped supporting my initiatives. They taught me that loyalty is a consequence of leadership. By far, I believe our greatest achievement was to see so many engineers grow their talent in this environment and now contribute to the global Zodiac Aerospace engineering community.

Definitely a lot of lessons learned as well that I cannot wait to apply onto my next assignment
.
Key words: Team development, Program Management, Leadership, Certification,
Configuration Management, Reliability, Process Improvement,

member_experience_collection.title: Software Developer
member_experience_collection.description:
My focus at Zoic has been primarily centered around two major projects; a multi-user digital whiteboarding application targeted for the Microsoft Surface Hub and a React web application to assist fashion industry professionals with collaborative design efforts by displaying interactive 3D models rendered and served from Google’s Cloud Platform.

On the whiteboarding application I devised strategies to improve ink stroke rendering efficiency, coordinated with Microsoft’s InkPresenter team on implementing custom libraries for tail-end eraser functionality, authored an SQL database as well as delivering the final product to the client.

I was involved with the React web application from its inception, performing preliminary research into various 3D JavaScript libraries and their ability to interact with externally sourced 3D models. As part of the regular Agile dev team, I designed React components along with their corresponding API’s and SQL data stores. I undertook a major code-refactor initiative involving modularizing all application components for reusability and rearchitecting for improved efficiency.

member_experience_collection.title: Software Development Intern
member_experience_collection.description:
As an intern at Experian, I was introduced to a number of production methodologies and and tools for developing and deploying microservices within a serverless architecture. I worked with a team of developers whose primary task was to populate a series of databases with credit information from the UK and Ireland, and to author API's exposing this data to subscribers on the Experian network. The subscribers included financial institutions, independent software developers as well as other teams at Experian.

I was fortunate enough to get my hands dirty on a large portion of the tech stack at Experian. I authored API's in C#, wrote unit tests, modified MySQL tables, interfaced with DynamoDB data stores, performed API tests with Postman and deployed services with Jenkins.

member_patents_collection.title: Method and apparatus for providing squad and auction in online sports game
member_patents_collection.description:
In an online sports game in which a user manages a team to play a match, a technique is provided for enabling a user to change a squad of a user-owned team and/or participate in an auction, even if the user is not running the game through a user terminal with a game client installed. A method for providing squads and auctions in an online sports game according to one embodiment of the present invention, wherein a squad providing device configures a squad setting page that is accessible to a user terminal of a user regardless of whether a game client is installed on the user terminal, and that allows the user to set a position of each of a plurality of characters included in a team operated by the user according to a selected formation; and, when the user terminal accesses the squad setting page, the user terminal displays the squad setting page displaying the preset squad on the user terminal, receiving position information for each of a formation and a plurality of characters from the user terminal to create a squad for a team owned by the user; and, when the user terminal terminates access to the squad setting page, transmitting the set squad to a game server providing a game service, thereby setting the set squad to be playable as a user's squad in a game when the user connects to the game server with a user terminal having a game client installed.
